be useful for reme as a *peer discovery* mechanism (finding which relay nodes serve a given routing key) rather than for message delivery. This would complement the existing mailbox model.\n\n**Recommendation:** Do not adopt DHT for message routing. Consider DHT-style peer discovery for finding relay nodes in a decentralized topology (post-v1.0, when multiple independent relays exist).\n\n### 2. UDP Direct P2P + NAT Hole Punching\n\n**Photon's transport stack** (`NETWORK.md`, `src/network/udp.rs`):\n- All traffic on a single UDP port (4383), with TCP on the same port as fallback.\n- Direct UDP between peers using IP:port from FGTW bootstrap.\n- NAT hairpinning workaround: bootstrap includes `local_ip` field (line 406 in `bootstrap.rs`) so peers behind the same NAT can reach each other via LAN IPs.\n- No actual NAT hole punching (STUN/TURN). Photon relies on FGTW knowing the peer's public IP from the bootstrap announcement.\n\n**Could reme benefit from direct UDP transport?**\n\nPossibly, but with significant caveats:\n- **Pro:** Lower latency for online peers; eliminates relay round-trip. Tier 1 (Direct) in reme's tiered delivery is the natural place for this.\n- **Pro:** Photon's approach of falling back through UDP -> TCP -> relay (`src/network/pt/mod.rs` lines 13-15) maps cleanly to reme's Direct -> Quorum -> BestEffort tiers.\n- **Con:** Without proper NAT traversal (STUN/TURN/ICE), direct UDP only works when peers have public IPs or are on the same LAN. Most mobile users are behind carrier-grade NAT.\n- **Con:** Maintaining a UDP socket consumes battery on mobile devices.\n- **Con:** reme's embedded HTTP relay already enables direct P2P delivery via HTTP, with proper mDNS discovery. Adding raw UDP is redundant for the LAN case.\n\n**Recommendation:** Not worth implementing for current scope. The embedded HTTP server with mDNS discovery already covers the LAN P2P case. For WAN P2P, a future WebRTC transport (with ICE) would be more robust than raw UDP. If direct