itment matches.\n\n```\nChallenger                              Responder\n    │                                       │\n    │  challenge + BLAKE3(                  │\n    │    challenger_nonce || target_rk)      │\n    │──────────────────────────────────────▶│\n    │                              check:   │\n    │                    commitment matches  │\n    │                       own routing_key? │\n    │                           yes → sign   │\n    │                           no  → 404    │\n    │  { signature }                        │\n    │◀──────────────────────────────────────│\n```\n\n**Pros:**\n- Single round trip (same as today)\n- Prevents blind enumeration — attacker must already know the target's routing key\n- Simple to implement\n- Backward-compatible if commitment is optional during migration\n\n**Cons:**\n- One-directional: responder still doesn't know who's asking\n- Attacker with a routing key list can still probe (but must be targeted, not blind)\n- Routing key is 16 bytes (truncated BLAKE3 of PublicID) — smaller search space than PublicID\n\n### Option B: Mutual challenge-response (two rounds)\n\nBoth parties authenticate. The challenger proves their own identity too.\n\n```\nChallenger                              Responder\n    │                                       │\n    │  Round 1:                             │\n    │  challenger_pubkey + challenge_a      │\n    │  + commitment (target routing_key)    │\n    │──────────────────────────────────────▶│\n    │                     verify commitment │\n    │                     check challenger  │\n    │                       is known contact│\n    │                                       │\n    │  Round 2:                             │\n    │  signature_b(challenge_a) +           │\n    │  challenge_b                          │\n    │◀──────────────────────────────────────│\n    │                                       │\n    │  Round 3:                             │\n    │  signature_a(challenge_b)             │\n    │──────────────────────────────────────▶│\n    │                       both verified   │\n```\n\n**Pros:**\n- Both parties authenticated — responder knows who asked\n- Responder can enforce policy (only respond to known contacts)\n- Foundation for trust level upgrades (#179) — mutual verification could auto-promote to `Verified`\n- Strongest defense against enumeration\n\n**Cons:**\n- Two extra round trips (3 total) — higher latency for discovery\n- More complex protocol and state management\n- Responder must hold challenger state between rounds (stateful endpoint)\n\n### Option C: ECDH-gated response (one round, encrypted)\n\nChallenger sends an ephemeral X25519 pubkey + the target routing key encrypted to the responder. The responder decrypts, checks if it matches, and only then signs — encrypted response back.\n\n```\nChallenger                              Responder\n    │                                       │\n    │  ephemeral_pubkey +                   │\n    │  Enc(target_rk, ECDH(eph, responder)) │\n    │──────────────────────────────────────▶│\n    │                    ECDH(own_mik, eph) │\n    │                    decrypt target_rk  │\n    │                    matches? → sign    │\n    │                                       │\n    │  Enc(signature, shared_secret)        │\n    │◀──────────────────────────────────────│\n```\n\n**Pros:**\n- Single round trip\n- Prevents enumeration (responder rejects non-matching requests silently)\n- Encrypted query — eavesdropper can't see which routing key is being queried\n- Encrypted response — eavesdropper can't see the signature\n- Reuses reme's existing X25519 + ChaCha20Poly1305 primitives\n- Conceptually aligned with reme's stateless encryption model\n\n**Cons:**\n- Requires the challenger to know the responder's PublicID (not just routing key) for ECDH — but the challenger already has this from the contacts list\n- Still one-directional (responder doesn't learn challenger's persistent 