            "content": "# Photon Messenger Analysis for Reme\n\n**Date:** 2026-03-27\n**Source:** [github.com/nickspiker/photon](https://github.com/nickspiker/photon)\n**Context:** Cross-project analysis of Photon — a Rust P2P messenger with rolling-chain encryption, custom DHT, and social attestation identity. Evaluated for patterns, lessons, and gaps applicable to reme.\n\n---\n\n## Project Overview\n\nPhoton is a ~44K LOC Rust monolith (67 source files, single crate) building a true peer-to-peer messenger. Early-stage — messaging not fully working. Single developer.\n\n| Aspect | Photon | reme |\n|---|---|---|\n| Architecture | Monolith (single crate) | Workspace (11 crates) |\n| Encryption | Rolling-chain (ACK-based advancement, 512-link chains) | Stateless MIK (ephemeral X25519 + BLAKE3 KDF + ChaCha20Poly1305) |\n| Key exchange | CLUTCH (8-algorithm ceremony, 550KB payload) | Single X25519 ECDH per message |\n| Transport | UDP direct P2P + TCP fallback + FGTW relay | HTTP mailbox + MQTT + embedded HTTP relay |\n| Discovery | Raw UDP broadcast + FGTW DHT | mDNS-SD (`_reme._tcp.local.`) |\n| Identity | Handle-based + social attestation (2-human vouching) | PublicID (32-byte X25519 key) |\n| Storage | Encrypted flat files (ChaCha20Poly1305) | Plaintext SQLite |\n| GUI | Custom winit + wgpu/softbuffer + cosmic-text | TUI (ratatui + crossterm) |\n| Forward secrecy | Yes (chain advancement destroys past keys) | No (MIK compromise exposes all) |\n| DTN tolerance | Poor (ACK-dependent, ordered processing) | Excellent (any message independently decryptable) |\n| Post-quantum | FrodoKEM, NTRU, HQC, McEliece (via CLUTCH) | None |\n\n---\n\n## What reme is already doing better\n\n### Stateless encryption for DTN\n\nPhoton's rolling-chain requires ACK-based advancement and ordered message processing. Lost or delayed messages block the chain — chained salt means M2 can't be decrypted without M1's plaintext (`CHAIN.md` section 3.2). reme's ephemeral-keypair-per-message model is strictly superior for delay-tolerant scenarios where messages arrive days apart in arbitrary order.\n\n### mDNS-SD discovery\n\nPhoton uses raw UDP broadcast to `255.255.255.255:4383` — doesn't cross VLANs, leaks `handle_proof` in the clear, no service type abstraction. reme's mDNS with privacy-preserving instance names, `DiscoveryBackend` trait, and HTTP challenge-response verification is more robust and extensible.\n\n### Workspace architecture\n\nPhoton's monolith led to a `Contact` god struct (`src/types/contact.rs:116-181`) with 35+ fields mixing domain state, crypto ceremony booleans (6 flags for CLUTCH state tracking), UI rendering cache (`indicator_x/y`, `avatar_scaled_diameter`), and network state. reme's crate separation enforces clean boundaries — `reme-identity` can't accidentally depend on `reme-storage`.\n\n### State machines\n\nreme uses proper enum-based phase tracking (`TieredDeliveryPhase`). Photon tracks CLUTCH ceremony state via boolean flags on the Contact struct — a combinatorial minefield where many flag combinations are invalid.\n\n### Error handling\n\nreme uses `thiserror` derives and `#[non_exhaustive]` on public enums. Photon hand-writes `Display` impls and has no `#[non_exhaustive]`.\n\n---\n\n## Actionable takeaways\n\n### High priority\n\n#### 1. Storage encryption at rest\n\n**Gap:** reme stores everything in plaintext SQLite — messages, contacts, keys, outbox state. Photon encrypts every file with per-domain ChaCha20Poly1305 keys derived from device identity.\n\n**Options:**\n- `sqlcipher` (drop-in encrypted SQLite, used by Signal)\n- Application-layer column encryption for sensitive fields\n- Hybrid: sqlcipher + app-layer for defense-in-depth\n\n**Tracked:** #177\n\n#### 2. `Zeroize`/`ZeroizeOnDrop` audit\n\n**Gap:** Photon's `Seed` type (`src/types/seed.rs`) derives `Zeroize` + `ZeroizeOnDrop` for all secret material. reme should audit that MIK private keys, ECDH shared secrets, and KDF intermediate buffers across all crates are zeroized on drop.\n\n**Tracked:** #178 (broader audit), #126 (two specific gaps already identified)\n\n#### 3. Hybrid X25519 + ML-KEM for post-quantum resistance\n\n**Finding:** Photon's 8-algorithm CLUTCH ceremony (550KB payload including McEliece's 524KB public key) is overkill and hostile to constrained transports. But the quantum threat is real.\n\n**Recommendation:** Single hybrid KEM — X25519 + ML-KEM-768 (~1.1KB overhead). This is the industry-standard approach used by Signal's PQXDH and Chrome's Kyber hybrid. Negotiate via version flag in `OuterEnvelope`. V2 scope.\n\n### Medium priority\n\n#### 4. TrustLevel enum for contacts\n\n**Finding:** Photon's `TrustLevel` (`Stranger → Known → Trusted → Inner`, `src/types/contact.rs:188-194`) with explicit serialization is a good template. reme currently has no trust/verification level for contacts — auto-created contacts from incoming messages are indistinguishable from manually added ones.\n\n**Tracked:** #179\n\n#### 5. Mutual identity verification\n\n**Finding:** Both reme and Photon have identity oracle problems — the identity endpoint signs challenges for anyone without authentication. Photon broadcasts `handle_proof` in the clear (worse than reme). But reme's endpoint is still an unconditional oracle regardless of mDNS configuration.\n\n**Tracked:** #180 (four options with trade-offs, recommended commitment check as immediate fix + ECDH-gating later)\n\n#### 6. Sync records during peer verification\n\n**Finding:** Photon's pong messages include per-conversation \"last received time\" (`SyncRecord` entries in `src/network/status.rs`) enabling efficient retransmission of only missed messages. reme achieves this through DAG `observed_heads`, but a lightweight sync exchange during mDNS peer refresh could reduce unnecessary retransmission in Phase 2 maintenance.\n\n#### 7. WritePolicy distinction\n\n**Finding:** Photon's `MustSucceed` / `BestEffort` persistence policy (`src/storage/mod.rs:13-20`) is elegant. `MustSucceed` does write-to-tmp + fsync + atomic rename + read-back verification. `BestEffort` skips verification. Chain state and crypto material use `MustSucceed`; avatars use `BestEffort`.\n\n**Application for reme:** outbox state and message persistence should be `MustSucceed`; display preferences and UI state should be `BestEffort`.\n\n### Low priority / future reference\n\n#### 8. Zero-metadata-leakage filenames\n\nPhoton derives opaque filenames via `spaghettify(blake3(identity_seed || device_secret || domain))` then base64-encodes them (`src/storage/flat.rs`). An observer of the filesystem learns nothing about contacts. Relevant if reme ever stores files outside SQLite (attachments, bundle exports).\n\n#### 9. Tick-driven fallback cascade\n\nPhoton's PT `tick()` function (`src/network/pt/mod.rs:486-589`) implements clean escalation (UDP retry → TCP parallel → relay fallback) in a single periodic state machine. Design pattern reference for outbox improvements.\n\n#### 10. Local IP in relay peer records\n\nPhoton's FGTW bootstrap includes `local_ip` field (`src/network/fgtw/bootstrap.rs:566-584`) so peers behind the same NAT can reach each other via LAN IPs. When reme has WAN relays, this would help with NAT hairpinning.\n\n---\n\n## What NOT to adopt\n\n### Rolling-chain encryption\n\nIncompatible with reme's DTN-first design. ACK-dependent chain advancement creates ordering dependencies. A lost message blocks the entire chain. The forward secrecy it provides is real, but the DTN cost is unacceptable for reme's use case.\n\n### `prev_content_hash` for \"opportunistic forward secrecy\"\n\nInitially seemed appealing (mix hash of last received message into ephemeral key derivation). On analysis: doesn't actually provide meaningful forward secrecy — an attacker who compromises MIK decrypts message 1 (no predecessor), then cascades forward through the chain. Creates ordering dependencies incompatible with DTN. The DAG already has content hashes (`prev_self`, `observed_heads`) — the reason we don't use them for key derivation is precisely this.\n\n### Spaghettify\n\nCustom \"chaos amplifier\" (`src/crypto/clutch.rs:424-597`) using trigonometric functions, Spirix floats, U256 arithmetic, and data-dependent operation selection. Cryptographically unsound — relies on \"provable irreversibility through information destruction\" rather than well-studied primitives. BLAKE3 with domain separation is strictly better.\n\n### Smear hash\n\nXOR of BLAKE3, SHA3, and SHA-512 outputs (`src/crypto/clutch.rs:21-43`). Defense-in-depth theater — XOR-combining hash outputs provides no meaningful security beyond the strongest individual hash. Single strong hash is sufficient.\n\n### Raw UDP transport\n\nPhoton's direct UDP P2P works on LAN but lacks proper NAT traversal (no STUN/TURN/ICE). reme's embedded HTTP relay already covers LAN P2P. For WAN P2P, WebRTC would be more robust.\n\n### Blast-256 congestion control\n\nPhoton's PT window (`src/network/pt/window.rs:104-223`) blasts 256 packets simultaneously, then backfills gaps. Too aggressive for shared internet paths — would starve other TCP connections. Standard CUBIC or BBR would be appropriate if reme ever adds UDP transport.\n\n### VSF custom binary format\n\nPhoton's Versatile Storage Format is self-describing with typed fields, schema versioning, and per-record signatures. Interesting but unnecessary for reme — `postcard` (serde) is simpler, leverages Rust's type system directly, and is well-maintained.\n\n### Boolean flag state machines\n\nPhoton tracks CLUTCH ceremony state via 6+ boolean flags on the `Contact` struct. Combinatorial explosion of invalid states. reme's enum-based approach is already correct — maintain this discipline.\n\n---\n\n## Crypto comparison summary\n\n| Property | Photon (CHAIN + CLUTCH) | reme (MIK stateless) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Forward secrecy | Yes (chain advance destroys past keys) | No (MIK compromise exposes all) |\n| DTN tolerance | Poor (ACK-dependent, ordered processing) | Excellent (independent decryption) |\n| Message reordering | Must buffer and process in order | Fully tolerant |\n| State per conversation | 16KB per participant (512-link chain) | Zero |\n| Offline resilience | Chain desync risk | No desync possible |\n| Post-quantum readiness | 4 PQ KEMs in CLUTCH ceremony | None (X25519 only) |\n| Key exchange overhead | ~550KB (McEliece dominates) | 32 bytes (ephemeral X25519 pubkey) |\n| Signature scheme | Ed25519 (device identity) | XEdDSA (X25519 key for both ECDH and signatures) |\n\n---\n\n## Issues created from this analysis\n\n| Issue | Title | Priority |\n|---|---|---|\n| #177 | security: encrypt SQLite storage at rest | High |\n| #178 | security: audit Zeroize coverage across all crates | High |\n| #179 | refactor: rework Contact model and add TrustLevel | Medium |\n| #180 | security: mutual identity verification to prevent LAN identity oracle | Medium |\n",
