          "text": "Good news — `arti` is mature enough for this. Here's the analysis:\n\n## Tor Hidden Service as a Transport\n\n### The idea\n\nEach reme client runs an embedded Tor hidden service. The `.onion` address becomes a NAT-piercing, IP-hiding endpoint. Peers connect to your `.onion` address — neither side learns the other's real IP.\n\n### How it maps to reme\n\n| reme concept | Tor mapping |\n|---|---|\n| MIK (X25519 key) | Derive Ed25519 onion service key via BLAKE3 KDF + domain separation |\n| PublicID → `.onion` address | Deterministic: `BLAKE3(\"reme-onion-v1:\" \\|\\| MIK) → Ed25519 seed → .onion` |\n| Embedded HTTP server | Same Axum server, but listening on the onion service instead of (or alongside) a LAN socket |\n| Transport tier | Tier 1 (Direct) or Tier 2 — it's point-to-point, just slower |\n\nThe `arti-client` crate (now at 2.0.0) provides `TorClient::launch_onion_service` — a Rust-native API, no subprocess needed. Onion service support has been stable since Arti 1.4.0. Restricted discovery (client authorization) stabilized in 1.7.0, which could limit who can even *find* your service.\n\n### What it solves\n\n- **IP privacy on WAN** — the gap that killed Iroh. Neither peer learns the other's IP. The Tor network handles rendezvous.\n- **NAT traversal for free** — no STUN/TURN/ICE needed. Tor circuits bypass NAT entirely.\n- **Stable addressing** — `.onion` persists across IP changes, ISP switches, even country moves.\n- **Censorship resistance** — with pluggable transports (Arti supports `pt-client`).\n\n### What it doesn't solve\n\n- **Latency.** Hidden service circuits are 6 hops (3 each direction). Expect 300-800ms RTT. Fine for async messaging, painful for anything real-time.\n- **Bandwidth.** Tor circuits are slow — large attachments would be painful. Better suited as a signaling/message channel, not a bulk data path.\n- **Availability.** Onion services can be flaky. Rendezvous point selection, circuit build failures, descriptor publication delays.\n- **Startup time.** Publishing an onion service descriptor takes 30-60s on first launch. Subsequent startups are faster if the descriptor is cached.\n\n### Key derivation question\n\nTwo approaches:\n\n**Deterministic** — derive `.onion` from PublicID. Anyone who knows your PublicID can compute your `.onion` address and attempt to connect. Pro: no separate discovery needed. Con: `.onion` becomes a reachability oracle (can probe if someone is online).\n\n**Random + published** — generate a separate onion key, publish the `.onion` address via mailbox metadata or contact exchange. Pro: `.onion` isn't derivable from PublicID. Con: needs a discovery/exchange mechanism.\n\nThe deterministic approach is simpler and fits reme's model — if an attacker already knows your PublicID, they can already send you messages via the mailbox. Learning your `.onion` doesn't give them your IP (that's the whole point of Tor). And restricted discovery (client authorization) from Arti 1.7.0 could gate access so only contacts with an authorization key can even resolve the descriptor.\n\n### How it fits the tier model\n\n```\nTier 1 (Direct):  mDNS LAN peers (ephemeral HTTP) + Tor .onion (persistent)\nTier 2 (Quorum):  HTTP mailbox relays + MQTT\nTier 3 (Best-effort): Future BLE/LoRa\n```\n\nTor slots naturally into Tier 1 as a \"direct\" transport — it's point-to-point, just routed through the Tor network. The outbox would try Tor alongside LAN peers, then fall back to mailbox relays.\n\n### Practical concerns\n\n- **Binary size.** Arti pulls in a significant dependency tree. Not a problem for desktop, but would bloat mobile/embedded targets.\n- **Tor bootstrap.** First run needs to download a consensus (~2-5MB). Subsequent runs are faster with cached state.\n- **Feature flag.** Should be opt-in (`--features tor-transport`) since not everyone wants/needs Tor.\n\n### Verdict\n\nThis is actually a strong fit for reme's architecture. The DTN tolerance means Tor's latency isn't a dealbreaker — messages already survive hours/days of delay. The IP privacy guarantee closes the exact gap that disqualified Iroh. And `arti-client` being pure Rust with an async API means it integrates cleanly with the existing Tokio runtime.\n\nWorth writing a spec for. I'd scope it as a v0.7+ feature — after the current v0.5 (sneakernet) and v0.6 (LAN relay) milestones.\n\nWant me to create an issue or a spec doc?\n\nSources:\n- [Arti 2.0.0 release](https://www.sambent.com/arti-2-0-0-ships-tor-rust-rewrite-hits-major-milestone/)\n- [Arti 1.7.0 — onion service restricted discovery](https://blog.torproject.org/arti_1_7_0_released/)\n- [tor-hsservice crate](https://crates.io/crates/tor-hsservice)\n- [arti-client docs](https://docs.rs/arti-client/latest/arti_client/)",
