          "text": "Here's my opinionated shortlist, filtered for what's actually relevant to reme's design space:\n\n## Worth a deep dive\n\n### [Briar](https://briarproject.org/) — The closest cousin\nJava/Kotlin. Tor + Bluetooth + Wi-Fi Direct. **The** DTN messenger. Designed for activists under network shutdowns. Store-and-forward via Tor, mesh via BLE when internet is gone. Very similar threat model to reme.\n\n**Why study it:** They've solved problems reme will face — offline-first group messaging, Bluetooth mesh relay, Tor hidden service transport (exactly what we just discussed), and multi-transport fallback. Their [Bramble protocol](https://code.briarproject.org/briar/briar-spec) is well-documented. Known weaknesses in handshake forward secrecy and group message duplication are instructive.\n\n### [Cwtch](https://cwtch.im/) — Metadata-resistant groups over Tor\nGo. All traffic over Tor v3 onion services. No server ever sees sender-receiver pairs. For async delivery, they use *untrusted broadcast relays* — encrypted messages sent to all participants, only the intended recipient can decrypt.\n\n**Why study it:** The \"untrusted relay that broadcasts to everyone\" model is a fascinating alternative to reme's routing-key-based mailbox. Their approach to group messaging without a server learning group membership is worth understanding. The bandwidth cost is real but the metadata properties are strong.\n\n### [SimpleX](https://simplex.chat/) — No user identifiers at all\nHaskell. No user IDs, not even random ones. Uses temporary anonymous pairwise message queue identifiers — a different queue per contact, per direction. Servers see queues, not people.\n\n**Why study it:** Their queue-based architecture is a radically different take on the same problem reme solves with routing keys. The \"no persistent identity\" design is philosophically opposed to reme's PublicID model, but their analysis of why persistent IDs are a metadata risk is worth reading. Also, they've shipped and have real users — practical lessons on what works.\n\n### [Veilid](https://veilid.com/) — \"Tor but for apps\"\nRust. From the Cult of the Dead Cow. P2P framework with DHT routing, E2EE, runs on all platforms including WASM. More of a platform than a messenger — [VeilidChat](https://gitlab.com/nicecraftz/veilid-chat) is being built on top.\n\n**Why study it:** Pure Rust, similar tech stack to reme. Their DHT with privacy properties is more sophisticated than Photon's naive Kademlia. Could potentially be used as a transport layer for reme rather than reinventing P2P routing. Worth evaluating as a dependency vs. competitor.\n\n### [p2panda](https://p2panda.org/) — Local-first with DAG sync\nRust. Built on iroh. Uses BLAKE3, Ed25519, Double Ratchet, CBOR. Modular — pick what you need. Their data sync uses operation-based CRDTs over a DAG.\n\n**Why study it:** Their DAG sync approach is directly relevant to reme's Merkle DAG for message ordering. They've thought carefully about eventually-consistent state across offline-first peers. The modular philosophy matches reme's crate structure.\n\n## Worth a glance\n\n| Project | Lang | Key insight for reme |\n|---|---|---|\n| [Cabal](https://cabal.chat/) | JS | Append-only log (hypercore) for chat. Simple but effective offline-first model. |\n| [Berty](https://berty.tech/) | Go | BLE mesh + internet. Closest to reme's BLE tier ambitions. Their BLE driver code is battle-tested on iOS/Android. |\n| [Session](https://getsession.org/) | C++ | Forked Signal, removed phone numbers, added onion routing via Oxen Service Nodes. Shows what happens when you try to bolt decentralization onto a centralized protocol. |\n| [Jami](https://jami.net/) | C++ | GNU project, OpenDHT for discovery, peer-to-peer calls. Mature but sprawling codebase. |\n| [Sideband](https://github.com/markqvist/Sideband) | Python | Built on [Reticulum](https://reticulum.network/) — a DTN stack for LoRa/packet radio/serial. The most extreme DTN messenger. Directly relevant to reme's future LoRa tier. |\n\n## My ranking for a Photon-style deep analysis\n\n1. **Briar** — most lessons for DTN transport, Tor integration, BLE mesh\n2. **SimpleX** — most lessons for metadata privacy, queue architecture\n3. **p2panda** — most lessons for DAG sync, Rust modularity\n4. **Cwtch** — most lessons for Tor onion service design, group privacy\n\nBriar and SimpleX would be the highest-value analyses. Want me to fetch and analyze either?\n\nSources:\n- [Briar Project](https://briarproject.org/)\n- [Cwtch](https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=43367012)\n- [SimpleX — no user IDs](https://greycoder.com/simplex-the-first-messenger-without-user-ids/)\n- [Veilid](https://veilid.com/)\n- [p2panda](https://p2panda.org/)\n- [Iroh](https://github.com/n0-computer/iroh)\n- [SecuChart comparison](https://bkil.gitlab.io/secuchart/)",
