            "content": "# E2EE/P2P/Decentralized Messenger Landscape\n\n**Date:** 2026-03-28\n**Context:** Survey of experimental messenger projects in the E2EE/P2P/distributed/federated/decentralized space, evaluated for lessons applicable to reme. Prioritized by relevance to reme's DTN-first, multi-transport architecture.\n\n**See also:** [Photon Messenger Analysis](2026-03-27-photon-messenger-analysis.md) — deep dive already completed.\n\n---\n\n## Priority 1: Worth a deep dive\n\n### Briar — The closest cousin\n\n- **URL:** https://briarproject.org/\n- **Language:** Java/Kotlin\n- **Transport:** Tor + Bluetooth + Wi-Fi Direct\n- **Protocol spec:** [Bramble](https://code.briarproject.org/briar/briar-spec)\n- **Status:** Production, actively maintained (v1.5.17, March 2026)\n\nThe DTN messenger. Designed for activists under network shutdowns. Store-and-forward via Tor, mesh via BLE when internet is down.\n\n**Why study it:**\n- Solved offline-first group messaging, Bluetooth mesh relay, Tor hidden service transport, and multi-transport fallback — all problems reme will face\n- Bramble protocol is well-documented and peer-reviewed\n- Known weaknesses in handshake forward secrecy and group message duplication are instructive — shows what goes wrong when you eliminate servers\n- Their BLE transport is the most mature implementation of exactly what reme plans for Tier 3\n\n**Relevant to reme:**\n- Tor hidden service integration (directly relevant to potential Tor transport, see [Photon analysis](2026-03-27-photon-messenger-analysis.md) Tor discussion)\n- Multi-transport fallback architecture (compare with reme's tiered delivery)\n- BLE mesh for Tier 3\n- Offline-first group messaging patterns\n\n---\n\n### SimpleX — No user identifiers at all\n\n- **URL:** https://simplex.chat/\n- **Language:** Haskell\n- **Transport:** Server-relayed via temporary anonymous pairwise message queues\n- **Status:** Production, real users, actively maintained\n\nNo user IDs — not even random ones. Uses temporary anonymous pairwise message queue identifiers: a different queue per contact, per direction. Servers see queues, not people.\n\n**Why study it:**\n- Queue-based architecture is a radically different take on the same problem reme solves with routing keys\n- The \"no persistent identity\" design is philosophically opposed to reme's PublicID model, but their analysis of why persistent IDs are metadata risks is worth reading\n- Shipped and has real users — practical lessons on what works at scale\n- Their threat model documentation is thorough\n\n**Relevant to reme:**\n- Metadata privacy analysis (persistent ID risks, correlation attacks)\n- Queue rotation patterns (could inform routing key rotation for reme)\n- Server-side privacy guarantees (what a mailbox relay should and shouldn't know)\n\n---\n\n### p2panda — Local-first with DAG sync\n\n- **URL:** https://p2panda.org/\n- **Language:** Rust\n- **Transport:** Built on iroh (QUIC-based P2P)\n- **Crypto:** BLAKE3, Ed25519, Double Ratchet, CBOR\n- **Status:** Active development\n\nModular framework for local-first P2P applications. Data sync uses operation-based CRDTs over a DAG.\n\n**Why study it:**\n- DAG sync approach is directly relevant to reme's Merkle DAG for message ordering\n- Carefully designed eventually-consistent state across offline-first peers\n- Modular philosophy matches reme's crate structure\n- Pure Rust, similar tech stack — patterns are directly transferable\n\n**Relevant to reme:**\n- DAG sync and conflict resolution strategies\n- CRDT-based state reconciliation (could inform reme's gap detection)\n- Modular crate design patterns in Rust P2P\n\n---\n\n### Cwtch — Metadata-resistant groups over Tor\n\n- **URL:** https://cwtch.im/\n- **Language:** Go\n- **Transport:** All traffic over Tor v3 onion services\n- **Status:** Active development\n\nNo server ever sees sender-receiver pairs. For async delivery, uses untrusted broadcast relays — encrypted messages sent to all participants, only the intended recipient can decrypt.\n\n**Why study it:**\n- \"Untrusted relay that broadcasts to everyone\" model is a fascinating alternative to reme's routing-key-based mailbox\n- Group messaging without server learning group membership\n- The bandwidth cost is real but the metadata properties are strong\n- Direct Tor onion service experience (relevant to potential reme Tor transport)\n\n**Relevant to reme:**\n- Tor onion service architecture (complementary to Briar's approach)\n- Group privacy without server trust\n- Broadcast relay model trade-offs vs. routing-key-addressed mailbox\n\n---\n\n## Priority 2: Worth a glance\n\n### Berty\n\n- **URL:** https://berty.tech/\n- **Language:** Go\n- **Key insight:** BLE mesh + internet. Closest to reme's BLE tier ambitions. Their BLE driver code is battle-tested on iOS/Android — practical reference for Tier 3 implementation.\n\n### Veilid\n\n- **URL:** https://veilid.com/\n- **Language:** Rust\n- **Key insight:** \"Tor but for apps.\" From Cult of the Dead Cow. P2P framework with DHT routing, E2EE, all platforms including WASM. Their privacy-preserving DHT is more sophisticated than Photon's naive Kademlia. Could potentially be used as a transport layer for reme rather than reinventing P2P routing.\n\n### Session\n\n- **URL:** https://getsession.org/\n- **Language:** C++\n- **Key insight:** Forked Signal, removed phone numbers, added onion routing via Oxen Service Nodes. Shows what happens when you bolt decentralization onto a centralized protocol — instructive in what works and what breaks.\n\n### Cabal\n\n- **URL:** https://cabal.chat/\n- **Language:** JavaScript\n- **Key insight:** Append-only log (hypercore) for chat history. Simple but effective offline-first model. The append-only log approach is conceptually similar to reme's Merkle DAG.\n\n### Jami\n\n- **URL:** https://jami.net/\n- **Language:** C++\n- **Key insight:** GNU project, OpenDHT for discovery, peer-to-peer calls. Mature but sprawling codebase. Their OpenDHT experience is relevant if reme ever adds DHT-based discovery.\n\n### Sideband / Reticulum\n\n- **URL:** https://github.com/markqvist/Sideband\n- **Underlying network:** [Reticulum](https://reticulum.network/)\n- **Language:** Python\n- **Key insight:** The most extreme DTN messenger. Built on Reticulum — a DTN stack for LoRa, packet radio, serial, and TCP. Directly relevant to reme's future LoRa/Meshtastic tier. Reticulum's transport design for unreliable, low-bandwidth links is worth studying for Tier 3.\n\n---\n\n## Comparison matrix\n\n| Project | Architecture | Transport | DTN tolerance | Metadata privacy | Language | Users |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **reme** | Mailbox relay + P2P | HTTP + MQTT + mDNS LAN | Excellent | Routing key (partial) | Rust | Pre-release |\n| **Photon** | P2P + DHT relay | UDP + TCP + FGTW | Poor (ACK chains) | Handle proof (weak) | Rust | Pre-release |\n| **Briar** | P2P + Tor | Tor + BLE + Wi-Fi | Excellent | Strong (Tor) | Java/Kotlin | Production |\n| **SimpleX** | Relay (pairwise queues) | Server-relayed | Good | Strongest (no IDs) | Haskell | Production |\n| **Cwtch** | P2P + broadcast relay | Tor onion services | Good | Strong (broadcast) | Go | Active dev |\n| **p2panda** | P2P (iroh) | QUIC | Good | Moderate | Rust | Active dev |\n| **Veilid** | P2P framework | DHT + relay | Moderate | Strong (onion routing) | Rust | Active dev |\n| **Berty** | P2P + BLE mesh | BLE + internet | Good | Moderate | Go | Active dev |\n| **Sideband** | DTN mesh | LoRa + packet radio + TCP | Best | Moderate | Python | Niche |\n\n---\n\n## Recommended analysis order\n\n1. **Briar** — most lessons for DTN transport, Tor integration, BLE mesh\n2. **SimpleX** — most lessons for metadata privacy, queue architecture\n3. **p2panda** — most lessons for DAG sync, Rust modularity\n4. **Cwtch** — most lessons for Tor onion service design, group privacy\n\n---\n\n## Completed analyses\n\n- [Photon Messenger](2026-03-27-photon-messenger-analysis.md) — rolling-chain encryption, CLUTCH key exchange, monolith vs workspace, storage encryption gap, identity oracle issue\n",
