            "content": "# Briar Messenger Analysis for Reme\n\n**Date:** 2026-03-28\n**Source:** [code.briarproject.org/briar/briar](https://code.briarproject.org/briar/briar), [briar-spec](https://code.briarproject.org/briar/briar-spec)\n**Context:** Deep analysis of Briar — the most mature DTN-first encrypted messenger. Java/Kotlin, ~2500 source files. Production-quality, actively maintained (v1.5.17, March 2026). Protocol specs are peer-reviewed and well-documented (Bramble protocol suite).\n\n**See also:** [Messenger Landscape Survey](2026-03-28-messenger-landscape.md), [Photon Analysis](2026-03-27-photon-messenger-analysis.md)\n\n---\n\n## Project Overview\n\nBriar is the gold standard for DTN messaging. Designed for activists under network shutdowns. Two-layer architecture: **Bramble** (protocol) + **Briar** (application).\n\n| Aspect | Briar | reme |\n|---|---|---|\n| Architecture | Two-layer: Bramble (protocol) + Briar (app) | Workspace: 11 crates, flat orchestration |\n| Language | Java/Kotlin | Rust |\n| Encryption | BTP transport-layer (per-transport keys, forward secrecy via rotation) | Stateless MIK (ephemeral X25519, transport-agnostic) |\n| Transport | Tor + Bluetooth RFCOMM + LAN TCP + Mailbox + removable drives | HTTP mailbox + MQTT + mDNS LAN |\n| Discovery | Encrypted property sync (addresses shared only with contacts) | mDNS-SD broadcast (visible to all LAN devices) |\n| Sync | BSP (Interactive/Batch/Eager modes with OFFER/REQUEST/ACK) | Outbox with tiered delivery (Direct/Quorum/BestEffort) |\n| Message DAG | Dependency-based, causal delivery enforced | Merkle DAG (prev_self, observed_heads), no enforced ordering |\n| Groups | Full support (private groups, forums, blogs, sharing protocols) | 1:1 only |\n| Storage | Encrypted DB (password-derived key) | Plaintext SQLite |\n| Forward secrecy | Yes (time-based key rotation, old keys deleted) | No (MIK compromise exposes all) |\n| DTN tolerance | Excellent (multiple sync modes for different latencies) | Excellent (stateless encryption, independent decryption) |\n| Contact exchange | QR code (BQP) + introduction protocol | Manual PublicID exchange |\n| Mailbox | Personal device (Tor hidden service, per-user) | Shared relay nodes (HTTP, multi-relay quorum) |\n\n---\n\n## What reme is already doing better\n\n### Transport-agnostic encryption\n\nBriar's BTP derives separate keys per transport. The same message cannot be forwarded across transports without re-encryption. reme's stateless sealed-box model means a single `OuterEnvelope` traverses any transport unchanged. This is strictly better for DTN scenarios where messages may hop through multiple transport types (HTTP relay → mDNS LAN → future LoRa).\n\n### Multi-relay quorum delivery\n\nBriar uses a single personal mailbox per user (Raspberry Pi running a Tor hidden service). reme broadcasts to multiple relay nodes with configurable quorum. This is more resilient — no single point of failure, no always-on hardware requirement.\n\n### Simpler DTN model\n\nBriar's BSP enforces causal delivery (messages held until all dependencies arrive). This is correct for consistency but can cause indefinite delays in partition scenarios. reme delivers messages immediately and uses DAG fields for gap detection — better for extreme DTN where weeks of delay are expected.\n\n---\n\n## Actionable takeaways\n\n### High priority\n\n#### 1. BSP OFFER/REQUEST for LAN peers\n\n**Finding:** BSP Interactive mode (spec: `BSP.md` Section 4.2.1) avoids sending data the peer already has. The challenger offers message IDs, the peer requests only what it lacks. Currently reme's Direct tier blindly pushes full envelopes to any reachable peer.\n\n**Application:** When reme has bidirectional LAN connections (mDNS peers with embedded HTTP), implement an offer/request exchange to eliminate redundant sends. This becomes critical as conversation history grows. The offer could be a compact list of ContentIds from the DAG.\n\n#### 2. \"Expected arrival time\" shortcut in outbox\n\n**Finding:** BSP Section 4.3 — a message can bypass its backoff timer if sending now via a different (faster) transport would reduce expected arrival time. Example: a message in Phase 2 (4-hour maintenance timer) should be retried immediately when a Direct-tier LAN peer comes online.\n\n**Application:** reme's outbox should check for newly available Direct-tier targets during Phase 2 maintenance, not just on the 4-hour tick. The `TargetHealth.avg_latency_ms` metric already exists — use it to compare expected arrival times across tiers.\n\n#### 3. BSP Client registry pattern for future extensibility\n\n**Finding:** Briar's most important abstraction. Each feature (messaging, groups, forums, introductions) registers as a separate BSP client with a unique `ClientId`, its own message validation, storage policies, and delivery hooks. The `ConversationManager` aggregates messages from multiple clients into a unified conversation view.\n\n**Application:** Before reme ships group messaging, introduce a trait boundary:\n\n```rust\ntrait AppClient: Send + Sync {\n    fn client_id(&self) -> &str;\n    fn validate_message(&self, msg: &InnerEnvelope) -> Result<(), ValidationError>;\n    fn on_message_received(&self, msg: ReceivedMessage, storage: &Storage) -> Result<(), ClientError>;\n}\n```\n\nThen `MessagingClient`, `GroupClient`, `IntroductionClient` each implement this trait. The `Client` orchestrator dispatches to the appropriate `AppClient` based on message type. This prevents `reme-core` from becoming a god struct.\n\n### Medium priority\n\n#### 4. Per-target backoff tracking\n\n**Finding:** BSP tracks `send_count` and `send_time` per message *per peer* (spec: `BSP.md` Section 4.1). reme tracks a single `next_retry_at_ms` per message. If target A fails but target B becomes available, reme must wait for A's backoff timer before trying B.\n\n**Application:** Track retry state per target, not just per message. The `successful_targets` set partially addresses this but doesn't handle the case where a previously-failed target recovers.\n\n#### 5. Transport latency in backoff calculations\n\n**Finding:** Briar's `maxLatency` per plugin drives key rotation periods and BSP retransmission timers (`BTP.md` Section 2.3). reme uses the same exponential backoff for all targets (5s base, 2x, 60s cap).\n\n**Application:** Feed `TargetKind` latency characteristics into backoff calculations. A Tor target (300-800ms RTT) needs different retry timing than a LAN peer (1-5ms RTT). Consider a `max_expected_latency` field on `TransportTarget`.\n\n#### 6. Group abstraction\n\n**Finding:** Briar uses `Group(id, clientId, version, descriptor)` as the universal container — every conversation, forum, and blog is a BSP Group with a deterministic `GroupId` (hash of descriptor). Per-group sync state, visibility controls per contact, and membership management are built into the protocol layer.\n\n**Application:** When reme adds groups, it needs:\n- A `Group` type with deterministic ID (hash of group descriptor)\n- Membership management (join/leave protocol)\n- Per-member message signing (XEdDSA already exists)\n- Group key distribution — pairwise (O(n) cost, Briar's approach) or group key agreement\n\n#### 7. Tor as mailbox transport (not direct P2P)\n\n**Finding:** Briar uses Tor hidden services for direct P2P connections — each contact pair maintains a persistent onion address. The mailbox is a separate Tor-accessed service for async delivery. The direct P2P approach requires both peers online simultaneously.\n\n**Application:** For reme, Tor fits better as a transport to reach existing mailbox relays rather than for direct P2P. Offer the relay's `.onion` address as an alternative endpoint URL. This keeps reme's async mailbox model intact while gaining IP privacy. Briar's rendezvous pattern (deterministic onion addresses from shared secrets) is worth studying for future contact exchange flows.\n\n#### 8. Contact introduction protocol\n\n**Finding:** Briar's Introduction Client (`Introduction-Client.md`) is a 6-message state machine: REQUEST → ACCEPT/DECLINE → AUTH (ECDH + MAC + signature) → ACTIVATE → ABORT. The introducer forwards but can MITM — acknowledged limitation, mitigated by post-introduction verification.\n\n**Application:** v0.5+ feature for reme. The MITM risk is inherent to any introduction protocol. reme's MIK-based approach makes it simpler (no session state to establish). When implementing, require mutual verification (TrustLevel upgrade) after introduction.\n\n### Low priority / future reference\n\n#### 9. BQP-style QR code pairing\n\nBriar's QR protocol (`BQP.md`) uses commitment-then-reveal to prevent MITM on key exchange. Both peers show and scan QR codes containing commitments, then reveal. Adds UX-friendly in-person contact addition. reme currently requires manual PublicID exchange.\n\n#### 10. Duplex vs Simplex transport distinction\n\nBriar's `DuplexPlugin` / `SimplexPlugin` split captures a real property — a LoRa link that can only send is fundamentally different from a TCP connection. reme's `TransportTarget` trait treats everything as submit/fetch. Consider adding `TargetCapabilities` flags for directionality when adding BLE/LoRa targets.\n\n#### 11. Bluetooth is point-to-point only\n\nBriar proves that Classic Bluetooth RFCOMM works point-to-point but NOT as mesh. No BLE implementation exists in Briar despite years of development. For reme's Tier 3, LoRa/Meshtastic is a better investment than BLE mesh.\n\n#### 12. Headless API server\n\n`briar-headless` is a REST + WebSocket API server exposing the same core as the Android app. If reme wants bots, web UIs, or multi-frontend support, consider a `reme-api` crate that wraps `reme-core::Client` as an HTTP/gRPC service.\n\n---\n\n## What NOT to adopt\n\n### Per-transport key derivation (V1)\n\nBriar derives separate encryption keys per transport (`BTP.md` Section 2.4). This would break reme's transport-agnostic envelope model — the same `OuterEnvelope` could no longer traverse multiple transports unchanged. Only revisit for V2 forward secrecy protocol.\n\n### Causal delivery enforcement\n\nBSP holds messages until all dependencies arrive. For DTN with weeks of delay, this causes indefinite hold-back. reme's deliver-immediately + DAG gap detection is the correct trade-off.\n\n### Personal mailbox model\n\nBriar's one-mailbox-per-user (always-on Raspberry Pi + Tor) is philosophically pure but operationally impractical. reme's shared relay model with quorum is more deployable.\n\n### BDF data format\n\nBriar's custom TLV format (6 primitive types, 2 containers). Unnecessary when you have serde — postcard is more compact, more ergonomic, and well-maintained. If reme ever needs self-describing messages, CBOR is a better choice than a custom format.\n\n### LAN discovery via property sync\n\nBriar shares addresses only with existing contacts via encrypted sync. More private, but cannot discover unknown peers. reme's mDNS approach is correct for auto-direct-known-contacts — it discovers first, verifies second. The privacy trade-off (#146 mDNS instance name) is being addressed separately.\n\n---\n\n## Protocol comparison\n\n### BSP Sync Modes → reme Tiers\n\n| BSP Mode | Bandwidth | Latency | Maps to reme |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Interactive (OFFER/REQUEST/SEND) | Lowest | Low (2 round-trips) | Tier 1 (Direct) — LAN peers |\n| Batch (SEND, wait for ACK) | Medium | High (1 round-trip) | Tier 2 (Quorum) — mailbox relays |\n| Eager (SEND, ignore timers) | Highest | High, lossy | Tier 3 (BestEffort) — LoRa/BLE |\n\n### BHP Handshake vs reme Identity Verification\n\n| Aspect | Briar BHP | reme LAN verification |\n|---|---|---|\n| Mutual auth | Yes (triple-DH: eph-eph + static-eph + eph-static) | One-directional (challenge-response) |\n| Forward secrecy | Yes (ephemeral keys deleted) | No |\n| MITM protection | Yes (if prior key exchange was secure) | Partial (#116 channel binding, #180 identity or