          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Yes. Let me map it out concretely.\n\n### What a per-chat session key buys you\n\nIf two peers establish a session (via something like BHP triple-DH or Signal's X3DH), subsequent messages within that session can drop everything that the session already provides:\n\n| Field | Current (stateless) | With session | Savings |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `ephemeral_key` | 32B every message | 0B (session ECDH) | **-32B** |\n| XEdDSA signature | 64B every message | 0B (session authenticates) | **-64B** |\n| `from` (PublicID) | 32B every message | 0B (known from session) | **-32B** |\n| `ack_hash` | 16B every message | 0B (derivable from session state) | **-16B** |\n| AEAD nonce | 12B | 0B (implicit from message counter) | **-12B** |\n| **Total saved** | | | **-156B** |\n\nCurrent overhead: ~242B → Session overhead: **~86B**. That's a 64% reduction.\n\n### What you'd add back\n\nA Double Ratchet (Signal-style) adds:\n\n| Field | Size | Frequency |\n|---|---|---|\n| DH ratchet key | 32B | Only when sender changes (not every message) |\n| Message number | 4B | Every message (for ordering within chain) |\n| Previous chain length | 4B | Every message (for skipped message recovery) |\n\nSo in a typical back-and-forth conversation: **8B per message + 32B on turn change**. In one-sided sending (offline recipient): **8B per message**, ratchet key sent once at the start.\n\n### Net result\n\n| Scenario | Current | With session | Change |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| \"hello\" (10B content) | 252B total (96% overhead) | ~104B total (90% overhead) | -59% wire size |\n| Typical text (200B) | 442B total (55% overhead) | ~294B total (32% overhead) | -33% wire size |\n| LoRa detached (10B) | 231B total | ~83B total | **-64% wire size** |\n\nThe LoRa case is where this matters most. 83B total for a short message fits comfortably in a 256B LoRa packet with room to spare. 231B barely fits.\n\n### The catch\n\nYou can't do this globally — it has to be **per-conversation, opt-in**:\n\n- **Session mode**: peers with reliable connectivity establish a ratchet. Low overhead, forward secrecy, but messages must be processed roughly in order.\n- **Stateless mode** (current): the DTN fallback. High overhead, no forward secrecy, but any message decryptable independently in any order.\n\nA message could carry a 1-bit flag in `flags`: `FLAG_SESSION_ENCRYPTED`. The receiver checks if it has session state for that sender — if yes, decrypt via ratchet; if no, fall back to stateless MIK decryption.\n\nThe negotiation could piggyback on the existing DAG: if both peers see each other's `observed_heads` updating regularly (i.e., they're both online and syncing), auto-upgrade to session mode. If messages go unacknowledged for a configurable timeout, fall back to stateless.\n\nThis is real architectural work though — probably v0.7+ alongside the Tor transport. Worth speccing now?",
