          "text": "Now I have the full picture. You're right — you already have a well-thought-out design for this. Let me correct my earlier analysis:\n\n## Correction: Async Noise XX, not Double Ratchet\n\nYou already have this specced out. The async-noise-handshake-v2 design is much better than Double Ratchet for reme because:\n\n**Double Ratchet breaks on message loss** — the DH ratchet advances on every turn change, and a lost ratchet key message breaks ALL subsequent decryption. Your DTN doc (`dtn-ratchet-limitations.md`) already proves this thoroughly.\n\n**Your Async Noise XX approach** piggybacks the handshake inside regular `InnerEnvelope` messages as a `HandshakePayload` variant (Hello → ResponderHello → InitiatorAuth → Ack). Once the 3-step handshake completes, you have a shared session key with forward secrecy. No continuous ratcheting needed — just a one-time key agreement that can be re-triggered (re-keyed) when both peers are online.\n\n### Per-message overhead with Noise XX session\n\nFrom the v2 spec, once a session is established:\n\n| Field | Current (stateless) | With Noise XX session | Savings |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `ephemeral_key` | 32B | Still needed (per-message ECDH for outer encryption) | 0B |\n| `encrypted_sender` | 48B (new in v2) | Needed (enables key-loss recovery) | 0B |\n| XEdDSA signature | 64B | **Dropped** — session auth replaces it | **-64B** |\n| `from` in InnerEnvelope | 32B | **Dropped** — use `encrypted_sender` from outer | **-32B** |\n\nWait — the v2 spec keeps the ephemeral key (it's still stateless at the outer layer for routing/decryption). The session key encrypts the payload, but the outer layer still uses per-message ECDH so that relays and the `encrypted_sender` recovery mechanism work.\n\nSo the actual savings are **~96B** (64B signature + 32B `from`), but **+48B** for `encrypted_sender` = net **-48B per message** plus forward secrecy.\n\nNot as dramatic as I projected earlier, but the real win isn't overhead reduction — it's **forward secrecy without breaking DTN**:\n\n- Session key encrypts the payload (forward-secret once ephemeral DH is deleted)\n- MIK layer still works as fallback if session is lost (graceful degradation)\n- No ratcheting, no message ordering dependency\n- Re-key via new Hello when peers want to rotate\n- DAG-integrated key deletion (keys deleted after message acknowledged, not time-based)\n\nThe design is already solid. The overhead question turns out to be secondary to the security gain.",
