          "text": "LoRa payloads range from 51B (SF12) to 222B (SF7). Let's see how far we can strip it down.\n\n## Current overhead inventory\n\nEvery byte that isn't content:\n\n```\nOUTER (plaintext routing layer):\n  version:          2B    — needed? version negotiation on LoRa?\n  routing_key:     16B    — who is this for\n  timestamp_hours:  4B    — when\n  ttl_hours:        3B    — how long to keep\n  message_id:      16B    — dedup\n  ephemeral_key:   32B    — per-message ECDH\n  ack_hash:        16B    — tombstone authorization\n\nINNER (encrypted):\n  from (PublicID):  32B   — who sent this\n  created_at_ms:    8B    — precise time\n  content:          var   — the actual message\n  prev_self:        9B    — DAG\n  observed_heads:   9B+   — DAG\n  epoch:            2B    — DAG epoch\n  flags:            1B    — flags\n\nCRYPTO:\n  AEAD tag:        16B    — integrity\n  XEdDSA sig:      64B    — authentication\n                  ─────\n  Total overhead: ~230B (with FLAG_DETACHED saving ~18B DAG → ~212B)\n```\n\nOn a 51B LoRa packet, that leaves **negative 161 bytes** for content. Even 222B gives you 10B. Useless.\n\n## The key insight: session keys unlock a completely different frame format\n\nWith an established Noise XX session, most of these fields become redundant — the session already binds sender, receiver, and key material. A LoRa-specific compact frame:\n\n```\nsession_tag:   4B    — truncated BLAKE3(session_key || \"reme-lora-tag-v1\")\n                       receiver scans active sessions for match\ncounter:       2B    — u16 monotonic (65K msgs per session, plenty for LoRa)\n                       doubles as: nonce, ordering, replay protection, message ID\nciphertext:    var   — ChaCha20Poly1305(key=session_key, nonce=counter_padded)\nAEAD tag:     16B    — Poly1305 (integrity + authentication)\n              ─────\nOverhead:     22B\n```\n\nThat's **22B total overhead**. Leaves **29B for content on 51B SF12**, or **200B on 222B SF7**.\n\nWhat was dropped and why it's safe:\n\n| Dropped | Size | Why safe |\n|---|---|---|\n| `ephemeral_key` | 32B | Session key handles encryption. No per-message ECDH. |\n| `routing_key` | 16B | `session_tag` replaces it — receiver matches against active sessions |\n| `from` (PublicID) | 32B | Known from session — only one sender per session |\n| XEdDSA signature | 64B | AEAD tag authenticates via shared session key |\n| `message_id` | 16B | Counter is the message ID |\n| `timestamp_hours` | 4B | Counter provides ordering. Receiver knows \"roughly now.\" |\n| `ttl_hours` | 3B | LoRa messages are ephemeral by nature |\n| `ack_hash` | 16B | No tombstone protocol on mesh |\n| `created_at_ms` | 8B | Not needed — counter + receive time |\n| `version` | 2B | Frame format identified by transport, not per-message |\n| DAG fields | ~18B | Already `FLAG_DETACHED` |\n| AEAD nonce | 12B | Derived from counter (deterministic) |\n\n## Can we go further? 12B overhead.\n\nFor extreme constrained mode, trade security margin for space:\n\n```\nsession_tag:   2B    — higher collision rate, but receiver has ≤10 active sessions\ncounter:       2B    — same\nciphertext:    var\nAEAD tag:      8B    — truncated Poly1305 (64-bit security vs 128-bit)\n              ─────\nOverhead:     12B\n```\n\n**39B for content on 51B packet.** Enough for a ~35 character UTF-8 message, a GPS coordinate, or an SOS signal.\n\nThe 8B AEAD tag means forgery probability is 2^-64 per attempt instead of 2^-128. For LoRa (low bandwidth, few messages, ephemeral sessions), this is acceptable — an attacker would need ~2^64 forgery attempts, each taking a LoRa packet's airtime.\n\n## The three-tier envelope design\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│  Full Envelope (HTTP/MQTT — Tier 2)                 │\n│  Current OuterEnvelope + InnerEnvelope              │\n│  ~242B overhead, transport-agnostic, stateless      │\n│  Works without any prior session                    │\n├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n│  Session Envelope (LAN/Tor — Tier 1)               │\n│  Noise XX session, drop sig + from                  │\n│  ~148B overhead, forward secrecy                    │\n│  Requires completed handshake                       │\n├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n│  Compact Frame (LoRa/BLE — Tier 3)                 │\n│  session_tag + counter + AEAD                       │\n│  12-22B overhead, session-only                      │\n│  Requires active session, no DAG, ephemeral         │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\nThe same message can be sent as a Full Envelope to the mailbox AND as a Compact Frame over LoRa simultaneously — the outbox just picks the right format per target. The content is identical; only the framing changes.\n\n## Open questions\n\n1. **session_tag collision** — with 2B tag and ~10 active sessions, collision probability per incoming frame is ~10/65536 ≈ 0.015%. Acceptable? If not, 4B gives ~0.000001%.\n\n2. **Counter rollover** — u16 gives 65K messages per session direction. For LoRa (low throughput) this is years of use. Re-key on rollover.\n\n3. **Session bootstrap on LoRa** — how does the first session get established? Probably not over LoRa itself (too expensive). Bootstrap via LAN/HTTP, then use the session for LoRa. Or: pre-shared key via QR code contact exchange.\n\n4. **Relay forwarding** — if a LoRa mesh relay receives a Compact Frame, it can't read the routing_key (it's implicit in session_tag). Relays would need to broadcast blindly or maintain a forwarding table. This is a fundamental trade-off of the compact format.\n\nWant me to write this up as a spec draft?",
