          "text": "Right. The critical constraint from the whitepaper: **\"The same encrypted envelope works on any of them\"** and the Starlink relay scenario — a LoRa node receives a message, buffers it, and uploads to Quorum when it gets internet. The LoRa receiver is NOT the recipient, it's a dumb relay.\n\nThis kills the session-tag-only compact frame. The relay needs:\n- `routing_key` to know where to forward\n- An opaque blob it can store and submit to a mailbox unchanged\n\nSo the question is: **one universal envelope format with the minimum overhead that still works when a relay is in the path.**\n\nThe relay needs exactly two things:\n1. `routing_key` — where to forward (16B today)\n2. The rest as an opaque blob — store and forward unchanged\n\nEverything else is between sender and recipient. So the design becomes: **shrink the sender↔recipient overhead, not the relay overhead.**\n\nWith a session established (via Noise XX over HTTP/LAN before the partition):\n\n```\nrouting_key:        16B  — relay needs this, non-negotiable\nencryption_mode:     1B  — 0x00=stateless, 0x01=session\nsession_tag:         4B  — recipient matches to session (only in mode 0x01)\ncounter:             4B  — nonce + ordering + dedup (only in mode 0x01)\nciphertext:         var  — ChaCha20Poly1305 encrypted content\nAEAD tag:           16B  — Poly1305 (inside ciphertext vec)\n                   ─────\nSession overhead:   41B + content\n```\n\nThe inner envelope in session mode is minimal — no `from`, no signature, no DAG (detached), just:\n\n```\ncontent:    var   — the message\nepoch:       2B\nflags:       1B\n            ────\nInner:       3B + content + 16B AEAD tag\n```\n\n**Total: 44B + content.** On 51B SF12: **7B for content** — one emoji, a GPS lat/lon pair, or \"SOS\". On 222B SF7: **178B for content** — a decent text message.\n\nStateless mode (current) remains unchanged — the relay doesn't care, it just sees routing_key + blob.\n\nThe relay's forwarding logic is identical regardless of mode:\n1. Extract `routing_key` (first 16 bytes, always in the same position)\n2. Store the entire envelope as-is\n3. When internet is available, POST to mailbox relay keyed by `routing_key`\n\n### What about `message_id` for dedup?\n\nThe relay can deduplicate by hashing the blob. The recipient deduplicates by `session_tag + counter` (session mode) or `message_id` (stateless mode). No explicit `message_id` field needed in session mode — saves 16B.\n\n### Can we shrink `routing_key`?\n\n16B is 128-bit. For relay forwarding, collisions matter — two users with the same routing_key get each other's messages (encrypted, can't read, but still a DoS/privacy concern). With 8B (64-bit):\n- Birthday bound: collisions likely at ~2^32 = 4 billion users\n- Acceptable for a niche messenger, risky at scale\n\nVerdict: keep 16B for now. It's the correct long-term choice and only costs 8B more.\n\n### Summary: one format, two modes\n\n```rust\npub struct OuterEnvelope {\n    pub routing_key: RoutingKey,          // 16B — always, relay-visible\n    pub payload: EnvelopePayload,         // variable\n}\n\npub enum EnvelopePayload {\n    /// Current stateless mode — works without any prior session\n    /// ~196B overhead (full metadata, ephemeral key, signature)\n    Stateless { /* current fields */ },\n\n    /// Session mode — requires prior Noise XX handshake\n    /// ~25B overhead (session_tag + counter + AEAD)\n    Session {\n        session_tag: [u8; 4],   // 4B — identifies session\n        counter: u32,           // 4B — nonce, ordering, dedup\n        ciphertext: Vec<u8>,    // content + AEAD tag\n    },\n}\n```\n\nA LoRa relay, an HTTP mailbox, and a BLE proximity node all handle this identically: read `routing_key`, forward the blob. The recipient checks the discriminant byte and decrypts accordingly.\n\n| Transport | Mode | Overhead | Content on 222B | Content on 51B |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| HTTP/MQTT | Stateless | ~242B | N/A (no MTU limit) | N/A |\n| HTTP/MQTT | Session | ~41B | N/A | N/A |\n| LoRa SF7 | Session | ~41B | **181B** | — |\n| LoRa SF12 | Session | ~41B | — | **10B** |\n| LoRa SF12 | Session (8B routing) | ~33B | — | **18B** |\n\n51B SF12 is brutal no matter what. But 10B is enough for \"SOS\", coordinates, or a status ping. 222B SF7 with 181B content is comfortable for text messaging.",
