            "prompt": "Perform a cryptographic security audit of the session encryption protocol specified in /home/leon0399/Projects/reme/docs/drafts/session-encryption.md.\n\nAlso read /home/leon0399/Projects/reme/WHITEPAPER.md for the broader protocol context (MIK, OuterEnvelope, InnerEnvelope, DAG, tombstones), and /home/leon0399/Projects/reme/docs/threat-model.md for existing threat analysis.\n\nFocus on:\n\n1. **Cryptographic soundness of the Noise XX adaptation:**\n   - Does the async adaptation weaken the Noise XX security guarantees?\n   - Is the DH pattern (ee, es, se) correctly applied across the 4 messages?\n   - Are the static_proof AEAD constructions sound? The spec says 48 bytes (32B data + 16B tag) — what is the 32B data? Is it specified precisely enough?\n   - Is the chaining key derivation specified? The spec references \"chaining key\" but doesn't define the KDF chain.\n\n2. **encrypted_sender field:**\n   - Is deriving the encryption key from `BLAKE3_KDF(\"rm-outer-sender-v1\", DH(ephemeral, recipient_mik))` sound?\n   - Using first 12 bytes of `message_id` as nonce — is this safe? `message_id` is UUID v4, so it's random, but is 12 bytes of a 16-byte UUID sufficient nonce entropy?\n   - Could this be an oracle? An attacker who knows a candidate sender MIK could encrypt it under the ephemeral and compare against `encrypted_sender` — but they'd need the ephemeral private key. Is this correct?\n\n3. **Recipient binding:**\n   - `BLAKE3_KDF(\"rm-hello-binding-v1\", DH(ephemeral, recipient_mik) || epoch)` — is this sufficient to prevent replay to a different recipient?\n   - Could an attacker who compromises the recipient's MIK use old bindings?\n\n4. **Epoch management and replay protection:**\n   - Is epoch monotonicity sufficient for replay protection in DTN where messages arrive weeks late?\n   - Could a network partition cause epoch desync (Alice thinks epoch=5, Bob thinks epoch=3)?\n   - The LRU cache for message ID dedup has a TTL — what happen