`s` encrypted under handshake state. reme assumes the responder's static key is pre-known (the MIK). |\n| `es` (msg 2) | Computed -- but **deferred** | **Deviation** | In reme V1 analysis, `es` is listed as computed by the initiator upon receiving msg 2, not by the responder in msg 2. The responder in reme does `ee` only for the proof; `es` is done by the initiator as `DH(e_A, mik_B)`. |\n| `-> s` (msg 3) | **Not transmitted** -- initiator's MIK already known via `encrypted_sender` | **Deviation** | Same reasoning as responder's `s`. |\n| `se` (msg 3) | Computed during `InitiatorAuth` processing | **Yes** | DH(mik_A, e_B) is computed (initiator side). |\n| Split | Single `blake3::derive_key(\"rm-session-v1\", ee \\|\\| es \\|\\| se \\|\\| mik_A \\|\\| mik_B)` | **Deviation** | Not a proper Noise split. See section 3. |\n\n**Risk: MEDIUM.** The DH computations (ee, es, se) are all present, so the core key material is equivalent. But the ordering, state progression, and transmission semantics diverge significantly from Noise XX.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Deviation Analysis\n\n### Deviation 1: Static keys not transmitted in handshake -- Risk: LOW\n\n**Noise XX behavior:** The `s` token in messages 2 and 3 transmits each party's static public key encrypted under the current handshake state. This provides identity hiding -- an observer who captures the handshake cannot learn the participants' long-term identities unless they can break the DH.\n\n**reme behavior:** Both parties' MIKs are assumed pre-known (you must be a contact to communicate). The sender's MIK is transmitted in `encrypted_sender` in the OuterEnvelope, encrypted with `DH(ephemeral, recipient_mik)`. The responder's MIK is looked up from the contact database.\n\n**Consequences:**\n- Identity hiding is handled differently but arguably better for reme's threat model, since `encrypted_sender` is encrypted in every message (not just during handshake).\n- However, Noise's `s` token serves a dual purpose: it also feeds into the transcript hash (`h`). reme does not hash the static keys into a running transcript. This means reme's handshake lacks transcript binding of identities -- a subtle but real difference.\n\n**Recommendation:** The final session key derivation includes both MIKs (`mik_A || mik_B`), which partially compensates. But this is not equivalent to Noise's MixHash of the encrypted static key ciphertext, which binds the identity to the exact point in the transcript where it was revealed.\n\n### Deviation 2: No running handshake transcript hash (h) -- Risk: HIGH\n\n**Noise XX behavior:** Noise maintains a running hash `h` that accumulates every piece of data sent or received during the handshake. Every public key, every ciphertext, every payload is mixed in via `MixHash(data)`. The `h` value serves as AEAD associated data for every `EncryptAndHash` operation. After the handshake, `h` is retained as a \"handshake hash\" for channel binding.\n\n**reme behavior:** There is no `h` variable. The spec does not define MixHash or any equivalent. Static proofs use a \"chaining key\" but this is derived from DH outputs only, not from a running transcript of all transmitted data.\n\n**Consequences:**\n- **Transcript binding is absent.** In standard Noise, if an attacker modifies any byte of any handshake message, the `h` value diverges and all subsequent AEAD operations fail. In reme, there is no equivalent mechanism that binds all handshake messages into a single authenticated transcript.\n- **Channel binding is unavailable.** Post-handshake, Noise provides `h` as a channel binding value that both parties can use to verify they completed the same handshake. reme has no equivalent.\n- **Unknown key share (UKS) attacks become harder to prevent.** Without transcript binding, it is theoretically possible for an attacker to cause two parties to derive the same session key while believing they are talking to different peers. The inclusion of MIKs in the key derivation mitigates this partially, but not with the same rigor as Noise's approach.\n\n**Recommendation:** This is the most significant deviation. Introduce a running transcript hash that accumulates at minimum: both ephemeral public keys, the recipient binding, both static proofs (as ciphertext, not plaintext), and the epoch. Use this as AAD in the static proof AEAD operations.\n\n### Deviation 3: No proper chaining key (ck) progression -- Risk: HIGH\n\n**Noise XX behavior:** Noise maintains a chaining key `ck` that is updated via `MixKey` after every DH operation. The progression is:\n\n```\nInitial:  ck = protocol_name\nAfter ee: ck, k = HKDF(ck, DH(e,re))     -- k is now live, n=0\nAfter es: ck, k = HKDF(ck, DH(s_r,e_i))  -- k updated, n=0\nAfter se: ck, k = HKDF(ck, DH(s_i,e_r))  -- k updated, n=0\nSplit:    k1, k2 = HKDF(ck, \"\")           -- two transport keys\n```\n\nEach DH result is chained through `ck`, and each intermediate `k` is used for encrypting the next handshake payload. The chaining ensures that each step's security depends on all previous steps.\n\n**reme behavior:** The V1 analysis shows: `session_key = blake3::derive_key(\"rm-session-v1\", ee || es || se || mik_A || mik_B)`. This is a single flat hash of all DH results concatenated, not a chained KDF. The session encryption draft (V2) describes \"chaining key\" in the context of static proofs but does not define the precise progression.\n\n**Consequences:**\n- **No incremental security.** In Noise, message 2's payload is encrypted under a key derived from `ee` only. Message 3's payload is encrypted under a key that incorporates `ee` and `es`. This means that even if `es` is somehow weak, message 2 still has some protection from `ee`. reme's static proofs use a \"chaining key\" but the spec text is ambiguous about whether this chains properly or is just `ee` for the responder's proof and `ee || es` for the initiator's proof.\n- **No intermediate encryption keys.** Noise uses the intermediate `k` values to encrypt payloads within handshake messages. reme relies on the outer MIK encryption for handshake message confidentiality, which is a different security property.\n\n**Recommendation:** Define the ck progression explicitly, matching the Noise framework's HKDF chain. Even if the outer MIK encryption provides confidentiality, the chaining key discipline ensures that the handshake is internally consistent and that static proofs are bound to the correct intermediate state.\n\n### Deviation 4: No proper split operation -- Risk: MEDIUM\n\n**Noise XX behavior:** After the final handshake message, Noise calls `Split()` which derives two independent transport keys from the terminal `ck`:\n```\nk1, k2 = HKDF(ck, \"\", 2)\n```\n`k1` is used for initiator-to-responder traffic, `k2` for responder-to-initiator. This directional separation prevents reflection attacks.\n\n**reme behavior:** A single `session_key` is derived. The spec does not describe directional key separation.\n\n**Consequences:**\n- **Reflection attacks.** If both directions use the same key, an attacker who captures a message from Alice to Bob could potentially replay it as if it came from Bob to Alice (if nonce management allows it). The separate `to` field in the InnerEnvelope and the XEdDSA signature would catch this in stateless mode, but the session mode section says \"per-message signature unnecessary\" -- which means this protection is lost.\n- **Nonce collision risk.** If both parties use the same key with independent counters, they could generate identical (key, nonce) pairs, breaking AEAD security entirely.\n\n**Recommendation:** Implement the Noise split operation. Derive two directional keys. This is a critical requirement if session mode drops per-message signatures.\n\n### Deviation 5: Handshake messages encrypted under MIK, not handshake state -- Risk: LOW-MEDIUM\n\n**Noise XX behavior:** Handshake message payloads are encrypted under the current handshake key `k` (which evolves via MixKey). Message 1's payload is cleartext (k is empty). Message 2's payload is encrypted under `k` derived from `ee`. Message 3's payload is encrypted under `k` derived from `ee` and `es`.\n\n**reme behavior:** All handshake messages are carried inside MIK-encrypted InnerEnvelopes. The handshake data itself is never independently encrypted under the handshake state -- it relies entirely on the outer MIK encryption for confidentiality.\n\n**Consequences:**\n- **Positive:** Handshake messages are indistinguishable from normal messages to an observer. This is better than standard Noise for metadata protection.\n- **Negative:** The security of handshake confidentiality depends on MIK, not on the handshake's own evolving keys. If MIK is compromised, all handshake data (including ephemeral keys) is exposed, enabling session key reconstruction. In standard Noise, message 3's payload has strong forward secrecy (level 5) even if the responder's static key is later compromised.\n- **Negative:** The Noise spec explicitly uses AEAD for handshake payloads as part of the transcript mechanism. reme uses AEAD for the static proofs but not for the handshake payloads as a whole.\n\n**Recommendation:** This is an acceptable trade-off for DTN/metadata protection, but document it explicitly as a design choice that weakens handshake-phase forward secrecy relative to standard Noise XX. The post-handshake session keys still provide forward secrecy.\n\n### Deviation 6: Counter-based nonce in session mode vs Noise nonce model -- Risk: MEDIUM-HIGH\n\n**Noise XX behavior:** Post-handshake, each CipherState has an independent 64-bit counter `n`, initialized to 0 after split. Nonces must never repeat. The counter is incremented after each use. If it reaches 2^64-1, the session must terminate.\n\n**reme behavior:** The spec says \"counter-derived nonce\" and \"16-byte session nonce\" in the overhead table, but does not specify:\n- Whether each direction has an independent counter\n- How the counter is persisted across crashes (the spec says ephemeral state is not persisted, but session keys are)\n- How DTN reordering interacts with nonce ordering (if the receiver requires monotonic nonces, out-of-order messages are undeliverable)\n- The exact nonce construction (is it counter-only? counter + direction bit? counter + random?)\n\n**Consequences:**\n- **Nonce reuse after crash.** If the counter is not persisted and the session key is persisted, a crash could reset the counter to 0 while retaining the session key, causing catastrophic nonce reuse.\n- **DTN reordering.** If the receiver enforces monotonic nonce order, DTN reordering makes messages undeliverable. If it does not enforce order, replay protection is weakened.\n- **16 bytes for nonce is unusual.** ChaCha20Poly1305 uses 12-byte nonces. The spec's \"16-byte session nonce\" in the overhead table is unclear -- is this a 12-byte nonce + 4-byte counter? Or a different construction?\n\n**Recommendation:** Specify the exact nonce construction. Use a monotonic counter persisted alongside the session key. For DTN tolerance, use a sliding window (like WireGuard's approach) rather than strict monotonic enforcement. Split the nonce space by direction (e.g., even/odd or high bit) to prevent collision when both parties encrypt under the same key -- though directional keys (deviation 4) are the better fix.\n\n### Deviation 7: `recipient_binding` has no Noise equivalent -- Risk: NEUTRAL (positive)\n\nreme's `recipient_binding` in the Hello message is `BLAKE3_KDF(\"rm-hello-binding-v1\", DH(ephemeral, recipient_mik) || epoch)`. This prevents replay of Hello messages to a different recipient.\n\nStandard Noise XX has no equivalent because in Noise, the static keys are not pre-known in the XX pattern (they are exchanged during the handshake). reme needs this because the responder's MIK is pre-known, which creates a replay surface that does not exist in standard Noise XX.\n\nThis is a **sound adaptation** to reme's specific threat model.\n\n### Deviation 8: Epoch mechanism has no Noise equivalent -- Risk: NEUTRAL (positive)\n\nThe monotonic epoch counter for replay protection and crash recovery is a DTN-specific addition. Standard Noise assumes reliable, ordered delivery. reme's epoch mechanism addresses a real gap in the Noise framework for DTN use cases. The collision resolution (higher epoch wins, then MIK comparison) is deterministic and sound.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Missing Noise Framework Operations\n\n| Noise Operation | reme Equivalent | Status |\n|---|---|---|\n| `InitializeSymmetric(protocol_name)` | None defined | **MISSING** -- no protocol name, no initial h/ck |\n| `MixHash(data)` | None | **MISSING** -- no transcript hash |\n| `MixKey(DH_result)` | Partial -- DH results concatenated | **INCOMPLETE** -- flat concatenation, not chained HKDF |\n| `EncryptAndHash(payload)` | MIK outer encryption | **DIFFERENT** -- handshake payloads not encrypted under handshake state |\n| `DecryptAndHash(payload)` | MIK outer decryption | **DIFFERENT** |\n| `Split()` | Single key derivation | **MISSING** -- no directional key separation |\n| `MixHash(prologue)` | None | **MISSING** -- no prologue support |\n\n---\n\n## 4. Async/DTN Adaptation Risks\n\n### 4a. Message ordering\n\n**Standard Noise** assumes messages are processed in exact order. reme's DTN model allows arbitrary delays and reordering.\n\n**reme's mitigation:** Handshake messages carry epoch numbers and are validated against persisted state. The stale message handling table in the spec is comprehensive. Messages from stale epochs are rejected. The MIK fallback ensures communication is never blocked.\n\n**Assessment:** The epoch-based approach is sound for DTN. However, the spec should explicitly address what happens if message 2 (ResponderHello) arrives before message 1's processing is complete, or if multiple Hello messages with the same epoch arrive.\n\n### 4b. Nonce reuse under DTN reordering\n\nAs discussed in Deviation 6, the nonce construction is underspecified. WireGuard solves this with a sliding window that accepts nonces within a window but rejects duplicates. reme should adopt a similar approach.\n\n### 4c. Simultaneous initiation\n\nThe spec handles this well with the deterministic role resolution (higher epoch wins, then MIK comparison). This is a genuine improvement over protocols that deadlock on simultaneous initiation.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Comparison with Other Adaptations\n\n### WireGuard (Noise IK, not XX)\n\n| Aspect | WireGuard | reme |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pattern | Noise_IKpsk2 | Noise XX-inspired |\n| Static key knowledge | Responder's key pre-known | Both keys pre-known |\n| Messages | 2 (1-RTT) | 4 (2-RTT) |\n| Replay protection | TAI64N timestamps | Epoch + message ID |\n| Nonce handling | 64-bit counter, sliding window receiver | Underspecified |\n| Async/DTN | Not designed for DTN | Core design goal |\n| PSK support | Yes (psk2) | No |\n| Formal verification | Yes (Tamarin) | No |\n\n**Lesson for reme:** WireGuard's sliding window nonce receiver is directly applicable. Also, WireGuard's use of a PSK modifier adds defense-in-depth that reme could adopt for high-security contacts.\n\n### Briar BHP (Triple-DH)\n\n| Aspect | Briar BHP | reme |\n|---|---|---|\n| Network model | Peer-to-peer, delay-tolerant | Store-and-forward, delay-tolerant |\n| Key exchange | Triple-DH with out-of-band shared secret | Noise XX DH pattern |\n| Authentication | MAC proof of master key | AEAD static proofs |\n| Server | None required | Mailbox relays |\n| Forward secrecy | Yes (via ratchet after BHP) | Yes (via session re-keying) |\n\n**Lesson for reme:** Briar does not use a running transcript hash either, but Briar's threat model assumes an out-of-band verification step (QR code exchange) that reme does not have. Without that trust anchor, reme relies more heavily on the handshake's own properties -- which makes the transcript hash absence more concerning for reme than for Briar.\n\n### Signal X3DH\n\n| Aspect | Signal X3DH | reme |\n|---|---|---|\n| Round trips | 0-RTT (prekey bundle) | 2-RTT |\n| Server required | Yes (prekey server) | Yes (mailbox) |\n| Static key transmission | Via prekey bundle | Pre-known (contacts) |\n| Forward secrecy | Partial (depends on one-time prekeys) | Full (ee + es + se) |\n| Deniability | Yes (implicit auth via DH) | Partially (XEdDSA signatures reduce deniability) |\n| Offline support | Yes (prekey bundles) | Yes (MIK fallback) |\n\n**Lesson for reme:** X3DH achieves authentication implicitly through DH structure without signatures, preserving deniability. reme's use of XEdDSA signatures in every message creates a publishable proof of communication. If deniability matters, consider switching to implicit authentication (DH-only) for session-mode messages. The static proofs already provide authentication; per-message XEdDSA may be redundant post-handshake.\n\n---\n\n## 6. KDF Domain Separation Analysis\n\n| reme Domain String | Purpose | Assessment |\n|---|---|---|\n| `\"reme-encryption-key-v0\"` | MIK encryption key derivation | Acceptable but should include protocol version |\n| `\"reme-nonce-v0\"` | MIK nonce derivation | Acceptable |\n| `\"rm-outer-sender-v1\"` | encrypted_sender key derivation | Different prefix convention (`rm-` vs `reme-`) -- inconsistency risk |\n| `\"rm-hello-binding-v1\"` | Recipient binding | Same prefix inconsistency |\n| `\"rm-session-v1\"` | Session key derivation | Same prefix inconsistency |\n| `\"rm-static-proof\"` | Static proof key derivation | No version suffix -- prevents safe rotation |\n\n**Risk: LOW-MEDIUM.** The domain strings are present but have inconsistent naming conventions and some lack version suffixes. In the Noise framework, the protocol name (e.g., `Noise_XX_25519_ChaChaPoly_SHA256`) serves as the initial hash, providing global uniqueness. reme has no equivalent protocol name initialization, so the domain strings are the only defense against cross-protocol confusion.\n\n**Recommendation:** Standardize the prefix. Add version suffixes to all strings. Consider initializing the handshake state with a protocol name string (e.g., `reme-session-xx-v1-25519-chacha-blake3`) analogous to Noise's `InitializeSymmetric`.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Risk Summary\n\n| Deviation | Risk | Impact if Exploited | Recommendation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| No transcript hash (h) | **HIGH** | Transcript manipulation, UKS attacks, no channel binding | Implement running transcript hash |\n| No chaining key progression | **HIGH** | Reduced incremental security, proof reuse risk | Implement proper HKDF chain per Noise spec |\n| No directional key split | **MEDIUM-HIGH** | Nonce collision, reflection attacks (especially without per-message signatures in session mode) | Implement Noise split() with two transport keys |\n| Underspecified nonce handling | **MEDIUM-HIGH** | Nonce reuse after crash, DTN reordering failures | Specify exact construction, persist counter, sliding window |\n| Static keys not in handshake | **LOW-MEDIUM** | Transcript binding of identity is weaker | Acceptable for reme's model; mitigate via transcript hash |\n| Handshake under MIK not handshake state | **LOW-MEDIUM** | Handshake-phase forward secrecy depends on MIK, not ephemerals | Document as deliberate trade-off |\n| Domain string inconsistency | **LOW-MEDIUM** | Cross-protocol confusion | Standardize naming; add protocol name initialization |\n| No formal protocol name | **LOW** | Cannot leverage Noise ecosystem tooling (Noise Explorer, formal verification) | Define protocol name for future formal analysis |\n| 4 messages instead of 3 | **LOW** | Extra round trip | Acceptable for DTN (Ack is optional) |\n| Recipient binding (addition) | **NONE** (positive) | Prevents Hello replay to wrong recipient | Good adaptation |\n| Epoch mechanism (addition) | **NONE** (positive) | Crash recovery, replay protection | Good adaptation |\n\n---\n\n## 8. Overall Assessment\n\nreme's session encryption draft captures the **spirit** of Noise XX -- three DH computations (ee, es, se) providing mutual authentication and forward secrecy -- but deviates from the **letter** of the Noise framework in several structurally important ways. The two HIGH-risk deviations (no transcript hash, no chaining key progression) are the most concerning because they affect the core security argument. In standard Noise XX, the security proof relies on the transcript hash and chaining key discipline to prevent subtle attacks (transcript manipulation, key confusion, identity misbinding). Without these mechanisms, reme's handshake relies on the correctness of the individual DH computations and the outer MIK encryption, which is a weaker security argument.\n\nThe DTN-specific adaptations (epochs, recipient binding, MIK fallback, collision resolution) are well-designed and address real gaps in the Noise framework. The MEDIUM-HIGH risk items (directional key split, nonce handling) are implementation-critical and should be specified before coding begins.\n\nThe comparison with WireGuard, Briar, and Signal suggests reme should:\n1. Adopt WireGuard's sliding window nonce approach for DTN reordering tolerance\n2. Consider whether per-message XEdDSA signatures are needed in session mode (deniability trade-off)\n3. Define a formal protocol name to enable future use of Noise Explorer or Tamarin for verification\n\n**Bottom line:** The spec should be revised to add a transcript hash, a proper HKDF chain, directional key split, and precise nonce handling before implementation. The DTN adaptations are sound and can be preserved as-is.\n\n---\n\nKey files examined:\n- `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/docs/drafts/session-encryption.md` -- the session encryption spec under review\n- `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/spec/analysis/async-noise-handshake.md` -- V1 design document\n- `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/spec/analysis/async-noise-handshake-v2.md` -- V2 analysis\n- `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-encryption/src/lib.rs` -- current MIK encryption implementation\n\nSources:\n- [Noise Protocol Framework Specification](https://noiseprotocol.org/noise.html)\n- [Analyzing the Noise Protocol Framework (PKC 2020)](https://www.iacr.org/archive/pkc2020/12110122/12110122.pdf)\n- [libp2p Noise XX Specification](https://github.com/libp2p/specs/blob/master/noise/README.md)\n- [WireGuard Protocol](https://www.wireguard.com/protocol/)\n- [Signal X3DH Specification](https://signal.org/docs/specifications/x3dh/)\n- [Briar BHP Specification](https://code.briarproject.org/briar/briar-spec/blob/master/protocols/BHP.md)\n- [Noise Explorer](https://eprint.iacr.org/2018/766.pdf)\n- [Briar Cryptographic Analysis (ETH Zurich)](https://ethz.ch/content/dam/ethz/special-interest/infk/inst-infsec/appliedcrypto/education/theses/report_YuanmingSong.pdf)</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>65790</total_tokens><tool_uses>21</tool_uses><duration_ms>313839</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/4ca7ec16-3e71-496c-91e6-56c7de96f6b4/tasks/afa56284aac601ab4.output",
